! FAQ

;Why isn't this just a fork of souk21/commandpalette?
:Souk21's data model is flat — one input, one list, terminal Enter. The cascade model is a stack of stages with right-arrow drilling and per-entity action menus (opened on Right for typed catalogue rows, on Space for any tiddler with applicable actions). Retrofitting a stage stack into souk21's widget meant fighting its assumptions on every change. Building fresh ended up smaller (~500 LOC vs souk21's 1100) and the data model is the protocol.

;How does this differ from a flat command palette?
:Flat palettes (souk21, VS Code's Cmd-P) treat every option as a terminal action: pick → fire → done. Cascading palettes treat picks as ''entry points into a graph''. Pick a person → see what you can do with them. Pick "Assigned Teams" → see their teams. Pick a team → see what you can do with that team. The graph composes — you discover what's possible by drilling, not by memorizing.

;Can I have a flat-palette mode where Enter on a result just navigates without showing the action menu?
:Yes — that's already the default. Enter fires the entity type's `ca-default: yes` action (typically "Open"). Right-arrow (catalogue rows) or Space (any row) opens the action menu. The flat-palette feel is preserved for users who just want to navigate; the cascade is available when they want it.

;Does the palette work in [[appify|$:/plugins/rimir/appify]] mode?
:Yes. The widget mounts in `document.body` via a startup module rather than via `$:/tags/AboveStory`, so it's independent of the page template — including appify's substituted UI.

;Can I rebind the hotkey?
:Edit `$:/config/shortcuts/rimir-cascade-palette-open`. Default is `ctrl+space`. ''Important:'' the tiddler body must have no trailing newline (TW's keyboard parser reads the raw text including the `\n`). When editing via the wiki UI this is usually handled, but if you edit the file directly, verify with `xxd`.

;Why don't I see person/team/task actions in tree views (''By namespace'', ''By parent'', ''Hybrid'')?
:Three action-discovery paths run in parallel — union, deduplicated by action title. ''(1) Catalogue:'' `ca-entity-type` matches the row's bound type (set by `ca-channel-row-entity-type` on the emitting channel). That's how the ''Entries'' view surfaces actions. Tree-view channels don't bind an entityType, so this path alone produces nothing in them. ''(2) Configured-field auto-derive:'' when the wiki sets `$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/entity-type-field` to a field name (e.g. `rimir/kind` ≥ 0.1.50 presets it to `kind.type` — the universal type-marker stamped on every kind-instance), an action's `ca-entity-type: <X>` ''also'' matches any row whose tiddler carries `<configured-field>: <X>`. With the kind plugin installed, every catalogue action automatically surfaces on Space in any view — zero per-action authoring changes. ''(3) Filter path:'' `ca-applies` is a filter evaluated with `<currentTiddler>` = the row title. Use it for cross-cutting actions that aren't kind-bound (e.g. ''Open URL'' on any tiddler with a `url` field) or for selective scope finer than a kind label.

;How do I open the action menu on a row in a tree view?
:Press ''Space''. Right-arrow descends the tree container; Space short-circuits straight to the action menu (filter-discovered via `ca-applies`). Empty match → silent no-op (no empty menu pops up). This is the same gesture used for catalogue rows, just routed through filter discovery instead of entity-type binding.

;What's the difference between `ca-entity-type`, `ca-action-when`, and `ca-applies`?
:''`ca-entity-type`'' — the catalogue tag. Match on a string label set by the row's emitting channel. Use this for entities authored in a typed catalogue (orga-palette persons, tasks, projects). ''`ca-applies`'' — filter-based discovery. The action surfaces wherever the filter matches, regardless of view. Use this when the action should reach rows that have no bound entityType (tree views) or should apply by tiddler property rather than by catalogue label. ''`ca-action-when`'' — refinement filter. Narrows whichever path matched (catalogue or filter) by per-row state (e.g. only on rows that pass an `is-active` check). Combine all three: `ca-entity-type: person` to bind to the Persons catalogue; `ca-applies: [<currentTiddler>get[kind]match[person]]` to also surface in tree views; `ca-action-when: [<currentTiddler>!field[status][archived]]` to skip archived persons.

;Why is the engine generic — no orga knowledge?
:So the same widget can serve multiple domain catalogues. The orga-data-model catalogue ships in `rimir/orga-palette`. A private-data-model catalogue could ship in `rimir/priv-palette`. Both depend on `rimir/cascade-palette`. No engine changes needed to add a new domain.

;Will my custom actions break when this plugin updates?
:Action tiddlers tagged `$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action` and using the documented `ca-*` field schema are part of the public API. Field schema changes will go through semver — breaking changes only in a major version bump.

;How do I debug a cascade that "doesn't fire"?
:Open the browser console. The widget logs at three checkpoints during boot (mount, hotkey listener register) and one on every successful open-message dispatch. If actions silently no-op, look for the `[cascade-palette] action invocation failed:` error. Most common causes: filter syntax error in `ca-next-scope`, wikitext error in `ca-actions`, or trying to dispatch a navigator-routed message from a context with no navigator under `$tw.pageWidgetNode`.

;Does it work offline / standalone?
:Yes. The engine and catalogue are pure plugins; they work in any TW edition (Node.js server, standalone HTML, browser-only).

;Can I customise the look?
:Override the styles in `$:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/styles` (e.g. via a real-tiddler with the same title) or ship your own stylesheet tagged `$:/tags/Stylesheet`. All classnames are prefixed `rcp-` (rimir cascade palette).

;What's the difference between ''axes'' and ''children''?
:Axes group at the top of the descent (year → month → day buckets); children form the recursive tree at the bottom (descend tag-children indefinitely). They're orthogonal channels of the same descent — a channel can declare either, neither, or both. Set axes only → pure grouping. Set children only → today's recursive tree (e.g. ''By parent''). Set both → bucket the forest roots first, then descend each. The transition happens at `parentPath.length === chain.length`: the engine emits `channel.roots` narrowed by every parent bucket key as real tiddler rows, then ''`channel.children`'' takes over from there. Full mental model in the Architecture section.

;Why is my axis chain empty / not showing buckets?
:Three common causes. ''(1)'' The axis tiddlers themselves don't exist — `cpAxes.resolveChain` silently drops missing titles, so a typo in `ca-channel-axes` leaves the chain empty. Check the title resolves. ''(2)'' `channel.roots` is empty — no candidates to bucket. ''(3)'' For the implicit-channel case, you declared `ca-view-axes` but the view tiddler also has `ca-view-channels` set — explicit channels win over implicit fields, so the axes are ignored. Move axes onto the explicit channel.

;A tiddler appears under the "wrong" year in my mixed (axes + children) tree — why?
:Cross-bucket children. Past the axis transition, `channel.children` runs with `<currentTiddler>` = the parent ''tiddler'' you just drilled into — not the bucket path. A 2025-tagged child of a 2026 TOC tiddler will appear in the 2026 subtree because tag-child means "tagged with this tiddler", not "created in this year". Almost always what you want for tag-trees. If you genuinely need date-coherent descent, intersect a date predicate into `ca-channel-children` (e.g. `[tag<currentTiddler>get[created]format:date[YYYY]match<stage-1-picked>]`).

;Why does the same tiddler appear in multiple buckets?
:Your `ca-axis-key` filter returned more than one result for that row. The engine reads only the ''first'' result — but groupBy considers each tiddler exactly once per axis. If a tiddler's key changes between bucket-rendering and child-filtering (e.g. a filter side-effect or a stale cache), you can see ghost duplication. Bump the wiki — `wiki.getChangeCount()` invalidates the per-axis key cache; the next render is consistent.

;How do I reset a channel's axis chain back to the declared default?
:Delete the state tiddler at `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/channel-axes/<slug>` (slug = last `/`-segment of the channel's title; for implicit-channel views, the view title's last segment). The next palette open reads from the channel's `ca-channel-axes` / `ca-view-axes` again. There's no in-palette "reset" button yet — clearing each pill with Backspace works too, since an empty chain falls back to the declared default.

;The shipped ''By field'' axis adds with empty params — how do I fill them in?
:Open `$:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/channel-axes/<slug>` directly, edit the JSON, set `"params": {"field": "status"}` (or whatever field you want to group by), save. The next palette render uses the new param. A picker-side param prompt is on the roadmap — for now, the state tiddler is the editing surface.

;Will the axis chain make my big wiki slow?
:Probably not. Axis key results are memoised per `(axisTitle + paramsHash) × tiddlerTitle`, invalidated on `wiki.getChangeCount()`. For a 3-axis chain over a 2500-tiddler source: ~150ms cold first-render, near-zero on subsequent keystrokes / drills. If you do hit slowness, the usual culprits are an expensive `ca-axis-key` filter (it runs per row) or a very broad `ca-channel-roots`. Tighten roots first; consider caching expensive key computations into a tiddler field at write-time if necessary.

;Can a channel have ''multiple parallel'' axis chains, like Hybrid has parallel channels?
:Not on a single channel — `ca-channel-axes` is one chain per channel. But Hybrid-style composition still works: put two channels in a view via `ca-view-channels`, give each its own `ca-channel-axes` chain. Each channel's rows interleave at every node; the chain belongs to its emitting channel.

;How do I add 🌐 row-icons for non-`url` field names?
:Edit `$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/url-fields` — space-separated, in scan order. For e.g. `url website homepage source`, the resolver checks each field in turn and surfaces the icon for the first value matching `^(?:https?|ftp|ftps|mailto|tel):`. Trailing whitespace is trimmed. To add a new URL protocol prefix (`magnet:`, `vscode:`, etc.) you'd have to edit the regex in `widgets/cp-row-icons.js`'s `URL_PROTOCOL_RE`; the strict allowlist is deliberate so config text doesn't leak into the strip.

;Why doesn't Shift-↵ open the URL like in some other tools?
:Shift-↵ is already taken by cascade-palette as a silent back-compat alias for ''fire-and-keep-open'' (it's been bound that way since pre-0.0.50). Re-purposing it would break muscle memory for users who rely on it. ''Alt-↵'' is unused and maps mentally to "alternate action on this row" — that's the row-icon gesture. Single-icon rows fire that icon; multi-icon rows fire the `ca-row-icon-primary: yes` one (or the first applicable in display order). Clicking a specific glyph fires just that one.

;How do I copy a URL to the clipboard from a search result?
:''Ctrl-Alt-↵'' on a row with the 🌐 glyph. The shipped URL icon declares `ca-row-icon-alt-message: copy-payload`, which invokes `$tw.utils.copyToClipboard(url)` — TW core's clipboard helper (modern Clipboard API + execCommand fallback) — and emits a tm-notify so you see a brief confirmation. Author your own icons with secondary gestures via `ca-row-icon-alt-message` / `ca-row-icon-alt-action` / `ca-row-icon-alt-hint`. The footer hint switches to surface ''Ctrl-Alt-↵ copy'' whenever the focused row's primary icon has an alt action wired up.

;What's coming in future versions?
:The next milestone is ''context-driven actions'' — actions that operate on the entity currently selected in the running orga app (no need to re-pick). Also ''form stages'' for multi-field input (e.g. ''New Project'' with name + description + due-date inline). And eventually a builder UI so users can author action tiddlers without editing wikitext.

